<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10030b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10030b">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10030b"> 30(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> hare&apos;s belly / under soles / in C &mdash; / tattooed</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Parysatis, qui engagea son fils Cyrus, le jeune roi des M&eacute;des, &agrave; se r&eacute;volter contre son fr&egrave;re, lui fit parvenir une lettre <mark>dans le ventre d&apos;un li&egrave;vre</mark>. &hellip; Aeneas le Tacticien, qui vivait au ive si&egrave;cle avant J&eacute;sus-Christ, a racont&eacute; tous les &ldquo;trucs&rdquo; invent&eacute;s par les g&eacute;n&eacute;raux grecs et romains pour mettre leur instructions &agrave; l&apos;abri des surprises de l&apos;ennemi; lettres dissimul&eacute;es <mark>entre les semelles</mark> des messagers, communications cach&eacute;es <mark>dans un ulc&egrave;re du porteur</mark>, ou encore dans les pendants d&apos;oreilles de femmes. &hellip; Il raconte &eacute;galement que des messagers d&eacute;vou&eacute;s port&egrave;rent des nouvelles trac&eacute;es avec un poin&ccedil;on, et pour ainsi dire <mark>tatou&eacute;es sur leur corps</mark>. <font color="green">[Parysatis, who persuaded his son Cyrus, the young king of the Medes, to revolt against his brother, sent him a letter in the belly of a hare. ... Aeneas the Tactician, who lived in the fourth century BC, recounted all the "tricks" invented by the Greek and Roman generals to protect their instructions from the enemy&apos;s surprises; letters hidden between the soles of the messengers, communications hidden in a carrier&apos;s ulcer, or even in women&apos;s earrings. ... He also tells us that dedicated messengers carried news drawn with a punch and, so to speak, tattooed on their bodies.]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 22</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
